3.1 CALLING A MACRO FROM A COMMAND LINE          


               It is common to repeat an identical sequence  of commands
               many times in a manuscript, e.g.,
.FILL ADJUST COMPACT TURN ON "^O{^B^C"

               You could define the following macro:
.MACRO FAC $( FILL ADJUST COMPACT TURN ON "^O{^B^C" )$

               and then whenever  you want the whole  sequence executed,
               write simply:
.FAC

               The  body of  the  macro enclosed  between $(  and  )$ is
               substituted for its name and then scanned by  the command
               scanner.

               A macro may also have arguments:
.MACRO T(CHR) $( NOFILL TURN ON "CHR" )$

               which when called by:
.T(^B)

               expands to:
. NOFILL TURN ON "^B"



